ilable to historians of Islam and a systematic review of the sources they will confront. Problems of method are then examined in a series of chapters, each exploring a broad topic in the social and political history of the Middle East and North Africa between A.D. 600 and 1500. The topics selected represent a cross-section of Islamic historical studies, and range from the struggles for power within the early Islamic community to the life of the peasantry. Each chapter pursues four questions. What concrete research problems are likely to be most challenging and productive? What resources do we possess for dealing with these problems? What strategies can we devise to exploit our resources most effectively? What is the current state of the scholarly literature for the topic under study?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  aAbū Mikhnaf.  aAlmoravids.  aBaghdad.  aByzantium.  aCopts.  aDamascus.  aEgypt.  aJacobites.  aJazira.  aJerusalem.  aKhurasan.  aMediterranean basin.  aMesopotamia.  aNishapur.  aOrientalism.  aOttoman Empire.  aRed Sea.  aSassanians.  aSunna.  aTransoxiana.  aTunisia.  aUmayyads.  afatwā, Iraq.  ajizya.  amadrasa.  amerchants.  apapyri.  aqadi.  aquantitative analysis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691214238zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691214238423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691214238.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  